=========================================================
INTERFACE CONCEPT IN C++ (INTERVIEW NOTES)
=========================================================

Definition:
C++ does not have an explicit 'interface' keyword like Java or C#.

In C++, an Interface is usually implemented using an Abstract Class
containing:

1. Only Pure Virtual Functions (=0)
2. No Data Members (generally)
3. Virtual Destructor

An Interface specifies WHAT a class should do, not HOW it should do it.

=========================================================
WHY DO WE NEED INTERFACES?
=========================================================

Suppose multiple classes need to provide the same functionality but
implement it differently.

Examples:
• Payment Systems
• Logging Systems
• Database Drivers
• Shape Drawing Systems
• Printer Drivers

Interface provides a common contract.

=========================================================
REAL WORLD EXAMPLE
=========================================================

Interface:
Payment Gateway

Implementations:
• Credit Card Payment
• UPI Payment
• PayPal Payment

All implement:

pay()

But implementation differs.

=========================================================
BASIC SYNTAX
=========================================================

class IShape
{
public:
    virtual void draw() = 0;
    virtual ~IShape() = default;
};

This is an Interface.

=========================================================
EXAMPLE 1 : BASIC INTERFACE
=========================================================

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class IShape
{
public:
    virtual void draw() = 0;
    virtual ~IShape() = default;
};

class Circle : public IShape
{
public:
    void draw() override
    {
        cout << "Drawing Circle\n";
    }
};

class Rectangle : public IShape
{
public:
    void draw() override
    {
        cout << "Drawing Rectangle\n";
    }
};

int main()
{
    IShape* s1 = new Circle();
    IShape* s2 = new Rectangle();

    s1->draw();
    s2->draw();

    delete s1;
    delete s2;
}

Output:

Drawing Circle
Drawing Rectangle

=========================================================
WHY IS THIS AN INTERFACE?
=========================================================

IShape only specifies:

draw()

It does not specify HOW draw() works.

Each derived class decides its implementation.

=========================================================
INTERFACE REPRESENTS A CONTRACT
=========================================================

Interface says:

"If you inherit from me,
you MUST implement my functions."

Example:

class ILogger
{
public:
    virtual void log() = 0;
    virtual ~ILogger() = default;
};

Any derived class MUST implement:

log()

=========================================================
EXAMPLE 2 : LOGGER INTERFACE
=========================================================

class ILogger
{
public:
    virtual void log(string msg) = 0;
    virtual ~ILogger() = default;
};

class ConsoleLogger : public ILogger
{
public:
    void log(string msg) override
    {
        cout << msg;
    }
};

class FileLogger : public ILogger
{
public:
    void log(string msg) override
    {
        cout << "Writing to file: "
             << msg;
    }
};

=========================================================
USAGE
=========================================================

ILogger* logger =
        new ConsoleLogger();

logger->log("Hello");

Can easily change to:

ILogger* logger =
        new FileLogger();

No code changes required.

This is called:

Programming to an Interface.

=========================================================
WHY ARE INTERFACES IMPORTANT?
=========================================================

1. Loose Coupling
2. Extensibility
3. Better Maintainability
4. Easier Unit Testing
5. Runtime Polymorphism
6. Dependency Injection

=========================================================
EXAMPLE : LOOSE COUPLING
=========================================================

BAD DESIGN

class Application
{
    FileLogger logger;
};

Application is tightly coupled to FileLogger.

---------------------------------------------------------

GOOD DESIGN

class Application
{
    ILogger* logger;
};

Application depends on abstraction, not implementation.

Any logger can be plugged in.

=========================================================
MULTIPLE INTERFACE IMPLEMENTATION
=========================================================

C++ allows implementing multiple interfaces.

Example:

class IPrinter
{
public:
    virtual void print() = 0;
    virtual ~IPrinter() = default;
};

class IScanner
{
public:
    virtual void scan() = 0;
    virtual ~IScanner() = default;
};

class MultiFunctionPrinter :
        public IPrinter,
        public IScanner
{
public:
    void print() override
    {
        cout << "Printing\n";
    }

    void scan() override
    {
        cout << "Scanning\n";
    }
};

Output:

Printing
Scanning

=========================================================
INTERFACE VS ABSTRACT CLASS
=========================================================

Abstract Class
--------------
• May have data members
• May have implemented methods
• Partial abstraction
• Represents IS-A relationship
• Can maintain state

Example:

class Shape
{
protected:
    int color;

public:
    virtual void draw() = 0;

    void setColor(int c)
    {
        color = c;
    }
};

=========================================================

Interface
----------
• Usually only pure virtual functions
• Usually no data members
• Complete abstraction
• No state
• Represents capability/contract

Example:

class IDrawable
{
public:
    virtual void draw() = 0;
    virtual ~IDrawable() = default;
};

=========================================================
INTERVIEW TABLE
=========================================================

Feature               Interface      Abstract Class
---------------------------------------------------
Pure Virtual Functions   Yes              Yes
Normal Functions         Usually No       Yes
Data Members             Usually No       Yes
Constructors             No               Yes
State                    No               Yes
Object Creation          No               No
Purpose                  Contract         Partial Abstraction

=========================================================
WHY VIRTUAL DESTRUCTOR?
=========================================================

class IShape
{
public:
    virtual ~IShape() = default;
};

Reason:

IShape* p = new Circle();

delete p;

Derived destructor should execute properly.

Rule:

Any interface intended for polymorphic deletion should have a
virtual destructor.

=========================================================
INTERVIEW QUESTIONS
=========================================================

Q1. Does C++ have an interface keyword?

Answer:
No.

Interfaces are implemented using abstract classes containing only
pure virtual functions.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q2. What is an Interface?

Answer:
An interface is a contract that specifies what operations a class must
provide without specifying how those operations are implemented.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q3. How do you create an interface in C++?

Answer:

class IShape
{
public:
    virtual void draw() = 0;
    virtual ~IShape() = default;
};

---------------------------------------------------------

Q4. Why use interfaces?

Answer:
• Loose Coupling
• Runtime Polymorphism
• Extensibility
• Dependency Injection
• Better Unit Testing

---------------------------------------------------------

Q5. Can interfaces have data members?

Technically:
YES.

Practically:
Avoid it.

Interfaces should be stateless.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q6. Can interfaces have constructors?

Technically:
Yes, because interfaces are abstract classes.

Practically:
Usually avoided.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q7. Can we create objects of an interface?

No.

IShape s; // Error

=========================================================
INTERVIEW READY ANSWER
=========================================================

C++ does not have a separate interface keyword. An interface is usually
implemented as an abstract class containing only pure virtual functions
and a virtual destructor. It defines a contract that derived classes
must implement, promoting loose coupling, extensibility, and runtime
polymorphism.

